05201nam a22007215i 9780231530347DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011012670  a97802315303477 a10.7312/rich157702doi  a(DE-B1597)459261  a(OCoLC)979626515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB805b.R53 2011 4aB805b.R53 2011 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a190.9/0512221 aRichter, Gerhard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfterness :bFigures of Following in Modern Thought and Aesthetics /cGerhard Richter. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Logic of Afterness -- t1. Afterness and Modernity: A Genealogical Note -- t2. Afterness and Critique: A Paradigmatic Case -- t3. Afterness and Aesthetics: End Without End -- t4. Afterness and Rettung : Can Anything Be Rescued by Defending It? -- t5. Afterness and Translation: The Politics of Carrying Across -- t6. Afterness and the Image (I): Unsettling Photography -- t7. Afterness and the Image (II): Image Withdrawal -- t8. Afterness and Experience (I): Can Hope Be Disappointed? -- t9. Afterness and Experience (II): Crude Thinking Rethought -- t10. Afterness and Experience (III): Mourning, Memory, and the Fictions of Anteriority -- t11. Afterness and Empty Space: No Longer and Not Yet -- tAfterwards: After-Words -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGerhard Richter's groundbreaking study argues that the concept of "afterness" is a key figure in the thought and aesthetics of modernity. It pursues questions such as: What does it mean for something to "follow" something else? Does that which follows mark a clear break with what came before it, or does it in fact tacitly perpetuate its predecessor as a consequence of its inevitable indebtedness to the terms and conditions of that from which it claims to have departed? Indeed, is not the very act of breaking with, and then following upon, a way of retroactively constructing and fortifying that from which the break that set the movement of following into motion had occurred?The book explores the concept and movement of afterness as a privileged yet uncanny category through close readings of writers such as Kant, Kafka, Heidegger, Bloch, Benjamin, Brecht, Adorno, Arendt, Lyotard, and Derrida. It shows how the vexed concepts of afterness, following, and coming after shed new light on a constellation of modern preoccupations, including personal and cultural memory, translation, photography, hope, and the historical and conceptual specificity of what has been termed "after Auschwitz." The study's various analysesacross a heterogeneous collection of modern writers and thinkers, diverse historical moments of articulation, and a range of mediaconspire to illuminate Lyotard's apodictic statement that "after philosophy comes philosophy. But it has been altered by the 'after.'" As Richter's intricate study demonstrates, much hinges on our interpretation of the "after." After all, our most fundamental assumptions concerning modern aesthetic representation, conceptual discourse, community, subjectivity, and politics are at stake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAesthetics. 0aPhilosophy, Modern - 21st century. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny21st century. 0aTimexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z9783110